  "dateModified": "2026-03-06",
  "datePublished": "2026-03-06",
  "description": "Synthesis is the integration of multiple sources, ideas, or pieces of evidence into a unified argument. Where analysis works on a single piece of evidence, synthesis works across several, showing how they relate to each other and to the essay\u0026rsquo;s thesis.\nSynthesis is not summary. Summarizing three sources in sequence (\u0026ldquo;Smith says X. Jones says Y. Lee says Z.\u0026rdquo;) is a list, not a synthesis. Synthesis puts the sources in conversation: \u0026ldquo;Smith and Jones agree that X, but they disagree about its cause — Smith attributes it to A, while Jones argues for B. Lee\u0026rsquo;s data complicates both positions by showing C.\u0026rdquo;\n",
  "name": "Synthesis",
